Chazalviel’s diffusion model [64] is a classic kinetics model, which points out the dendrite growth occurred around “Sand’s time” (τs) (shown as Eq. 1), corresponding to the ion depletion in the vicinity of the negative electrode, especially at high current density. During the charging process, the cation is rapidly consumed, after which its concentration near the electrode surface is expected to drop to zero at the moment in time. Afterwards, a strong electronegative electric field absorbs and deposits a large number of cations in a short period of time, causing the growth of dendrites. This behavior is known as "Sand behavior," and this time is called Sand’s time:1τs=πDeC02μa+μZn2+2Jμa2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
